spanGrp.span: Today we are going to remember the history of this place, the history(Cast.) is the history(MT).
juiti vechoyore eto to taye'e ... istoria te pjoka , taye'e istoria eto taye'e 'chojriikowo .
Florencia 2018 confirme "to taye'e istoria te pjoka"
xwiti βeʧojoɾe ɛto to taje(ʔe)ʔistoɾja te phoka, taje(ʔe)ʔistoɾja eto tajeʔe ʧoxɾi:kowo.
Hoy queremos saber la historia, la historia de aqui.
In the past, in the old days, when our ancestors looked for this town,
kopeni te to konewokaeni te to ... no viochkonini te to natankopuiji pjoka 'wosaree'i ,
kopeni te to konewokəni te to no βjoʧkonini te to nataŋko te pwiçi phoka wosaɾeʔi,
Antiguamente, nuestros abuelos buscaron este pueblo,
where we live now, the town of Trinidad, here lived the indigenous people, like me.
viowrikoo'i juiti , 'wósare Trinra , ene eno tkowsano eno no indijenano nkutgiene .
βjowɾikoʔi xwiti, wosaɾe tɾinɾa, ɛne ɛnotkowsano ɛnono indixenano nkutçene.
donde estamos (vivimos ?) ya ahora, la ciudad de Trinidad, era su pueblo de ellos, indigenas como yo.
They were the first authorities in the past, in the old days.
eno ... nowgieñonini kparaakonini te to ... kopeni te to konewokaeni .
ɛno now.çje.ɲo.ni.ni kpaɾakonini te to kopeni te to konewokəni.
Ellos fueron los primeros que existieron como autoridades, antiguamente.
and they were looking for it (the town), the poor indigenous people.
ene eno ... eno ttankonri'i , eno no powriono indijenano .
Ellos fueron los que lo buscaron, ellos eran pobres indigenas.
ɛne ɛno ɛno taŋkonɾiʔi, ɛne ɛnono powɾjono indixenano.
Ellos fueron los que lo buscaron, los pobres indigenas.

u.seg: 02- The story of the city of Trinidad

spanGrp.span: Spanish-English translation by Françoise Rose | Spanish-English translation by Françoise Rose
Now this town has grown big, now this town is Trinidad.
xwiti phoka wosaɾe ʧopeɾipo, xwiti phoka wosaɾe tɾinɾa.
Hoy es una gran ciudad, es la ciudad de Trinidad.
And when they came out here, they named this place where Almacen is (today).
ene te to tyuchkompuiji te pjoka naejarechri'i pjoka tow'o pjoka Almasen .
ɛne te to cuʧkon pwihi te phoka najhaɾeʧɾiʔi phoka towʔo phoka Almasɛn.
Y cuando salieron aquí, lo llamaron el lugar donde está Almacen.
They named it "the rainbow", "rainbow", there was the location of the rainbow.
ene naejarechri'i to o'ekure , o'ekure , ene towris'owri'i eto to arko iri .
juste ahi es el paradero del arco iris (para ahi el arco iris).
ɛnɛ najhaɾeʧɾiʔi to ʔoʔekuɾe, ʔoʔekuɾe, ɛnɛ towɾisʔowri(ʔi) ɛto to aɾko iɾi.
Lo llamaron arco iris, ahí está su paradero, es el arco iris.
ene to naejarecho to o'ekure chu .
ɛnɛ to najhaɾeʧʔo to ʔoʔekuɾe ʧu.
It was hearing the...um... the people, whenever they were approaching, it was smelling their odor.
tasamuiji to ... manje'e ... no 'chañono , te to naetekpo'okyorenovepuiji tajukpuka tomuire to naep'a .
tasamwihi to manheʔe ʧaɲono, te to naetekpoʔokjoɾenoβepwihi tahukpuka to mwɛɾe to naɛpʔa.
Escucharía la gente, cada vez que se acercaban, olería también su olor (de ellos).
And it always rained, there was thunder and um... lightning, and it rained heavily.
ene tgiwnovepuiji , tekchárako eto to manje'e ... to 'maare , ene mraka tgiwo ,
ɛnɛ tçiwnoβe pwɨçi, tekʧaɾako ?to to... to maɾe, ɛnɛ mɾaka tçiwo,
Ja (siempre ?) llovio, hay trueno, rayo, llueve fuerte,
Then they were scared, they ran, our ancestors, but they bravely made efforts
ene tpikokwonri'ojno , tyjunopono , eno no viochkonini pero eno nakomesajiikorichjicha chu eno ,
ɛne tpikokwonɾiʔohno, cunopono, ɛnono βjoʧkonini pero (por isso) ɛno nakomesahi:koɾiʧiʧa ʧu ɛno,
pues tuvieron miedo, corrieron, aquellos nuestros antepasados, porque ellos tuvieron ese animo,
Our ancestors too, they were not cowards,
eno no viochkonini nomuire , wo taptuujono nomuire chu ,
ɛnono βjoʧkonini no mwiɾe, wo.tap.tu.ho.no no mwiɾe ʧu,
nuestros antepasados tambien, ellos no tuvieron miedo tambien,
they smoked the rolled cigarettes,... here, here, we have always smoked the tobacco we grow, they made their rolls of tobacco, and they were smoking it.
tsapkompuiji to nayroko to pjoka pjoka siempre to vsapiiko pjoka saware vsukre , vsukre , vsukcho tomuire pjoka saware , naepiako to maso , ene eno tsapiikonri'i .
tsapkompwiçi to najɾoko to phoka phoka siempre to usapiko phoka sawaɾe usukɾe, usukɾe, usukʧo to mwɨɾe phoka sawaɾe, naepjako tomaso, ɛnɛ ɛno tsapi:konɾiʔi.
fumaron, lo envolvieron, siempre fumaron tabaco que habian sembrado, hicieron mazo, fumaron.
This is what I know today, gentlemen, what our elders have always told, of the search for this town.
takee'i juiti tatanoviono , te to ... to nechogiene , to naechjis'onve eno viochkonini , te to natansirari'i pjoka 'wósare .
Ya sabia lo que los abuelos nos decian, de cómo ellos buscaron este pueblo.
takeʔi xwiti tatanoβjono, te to to nɛʧoçene, to næʧisʔonβe ɛno βjoʧkonini, te to natansiɾaɾiʔi phoka wosaɾe.
Así es hoy día, Señores, lo que sé, lo que siempre han contado los ancianos, de cómo ellos buscaron este pueblo.
And this lake here, they called it Laguna Suarez.
ene etoripo pjuena kogiure naejarechri'i Laguna Suare .
ɛnɛ ɛtoɾipo pwhena koçjuɾe næhaɾeʧɾiʔi Laguna Suare.
Ellos llamaron la laguna Laguna Suarez.
It (the rainbow) chased them, um... it (the lake) was foaming, it is um... that's its way of being angry.
taponojoknoveri'iji manje'e tkososomri'i eto to manje'e tasemowo eto .
taponohoknoβeɾiʔihi manheʔe tkososomɾiʔi ɛto to manheʔe tasemowo ɛto.
Los persigue (E: el arco-iris persigue la gente) / correteaban, sale la espuma, es su modo de enojarse de ella (la laguna).
People did not know the rainbows yet, um... they were still bad, they were chasing our ancestors.
chu wich'o taemotri'i eno 'chañonri'i eno o'iono manje'erich'o winarajonrich'o takojnopokri'i eno viochkonini .
ʧu wiʧʔo tæmotriʔi ɛno ʧaɲonɾiʔi ɛno ʔoʔjono manheʔe ɾiʧʔo winaɾahonɾiʧʔo takoxnopokɾiʔi ɛno βjoʧkonini.
Todavia la gente no conocia los arco iris, que todavia son malos, los correteaban nuestros antepasados.
And what I know is that our ancestors um... they were not cowards.
ene to njitgiene eno no viochkonini manje'e eno wo taptuujono eno .
ɛnɛ to nhitçjene ɛnono βjoʧkonini manheʔe ɛno wotaptuhono ɛno.
Lo que yo sé es que nustros abuelos... tuvieron coraje.
And they kept moving until they sank. They tamed the lake. It became docile.
ene nanosjirichjicha ajta to nasiopuekpuiji ; pjuena kogiuree'i masupo najichri'i , masupo .
ne peut pas être –ri dans nanosjirichicha car pas de ACT –ko après
ɛnɛ nanoshiɾiʧhiʧa hasta to nasjopwɛk pwiçi, pwhena koçjuɾe:ʔi (næmansuʧpo) masupo nahiʧɾiʔi.
Ellos siguieron (à avancer dans l'eau) hasta que ellos se zambullieron. Essa laguna lo amansaron.
Esso lo vieron. Había sus cosas ?
and... they say, this is what they tell.
Dicen asi, es lo que ellos contaban.
Now there are no more ancestors, they died.
juiti najinapotsero eno ... eno viochkonini tepenonripo
Negation.043 avec GN à la place de Pro, pas de IRR
xwiti nahinapotseɾo ɛno ɛno βjoʧkonini tepenonɾipo
Hoy no existen mas, nuestros antepasados ya se murieron,
but there is always a... one who knows how things went, and he tells maybe truthfully that it was like that.
pero emja ma ... ma techo to tnekpogne'o ene muechjis'o je'chupka te to ene ... ene takee'i .
Fl0: él sabia que el otro lo estaba haciendo *ee (il savait ce qui se passait). Cf. Nominalisations.012 --> intesnifier.
pero ɛmha mateʧo to tnekpoçneʔo ɛnɛ mweʧhisʔo hɛʔʧupka te to ɛnɛ ɛnɛ takeʔi.
pero habia siempre uno que supo, que cuenta la verdad asi.
And we were younger, it was in the past, when I grew up.
ene viti 'moyponono , etjo kopeni te to nutiripo te to njuukopo .
ɛnɛ βiti mojponono, ɛtho kopeni te to nutiɾipo te tonhukopo.
Pues nosotros somos nuevos, digamos que yo voy creciendo (en edad).
and well, this is what they were always telling about my grand-father.
ene bueno naechjis'onve ema ma nochkini .
es lo que contaban de mi abuelo.
And after that, one day, we went... I was a man then, I went to work.
ene takeptsero kope vyompo 'jironupo nñompo nkemtónepo .
ɛnɛ takɛptseɾo kope βjompo xiɾonupo ɲompo nkemtonepo.
Ya me sentí hombre, fue a buscar trabajo. (ya trabajé)
And this I haven't worked on, on whatever of the stories, or something else de.. um...
ene wipo etina ( na... ) nakemtoneji to tajpuka taye'ono to 'chojriikowono , ponapo eto to manje'eri'i ,
Ya no pienso de lo que sea de las historias
wipo ɛto nakɛmtonehi to taxpukan(o) tajeʔono to te ʧoxɾikowono, ponapo ɛto to manheʔeɾiʔi,; 'chojrikowono
Ya no pienso las cosas, les historias, otra cosa de estas cosas;
And now with my living here in the Trinidad town
ene juititsero te to nowrisra te pjoka 'wósare Trinra .
ɛnɛ xwititseɾo te tonowɾisɾa te phoka wosaɾe tɾinɾa.
ahora que estoy (vivo ?) aquí en la ciudad de Trinidad.
and there were thinking (in these things) too.
ene enjoo'i no manje'e tkopneriijono nomuire .
ɛnɛ ɛnhoʔi no manheʔ tkopneɾihono nomwiɾe.
Ellos (los antepasados) han pensando en esas cosas tambien,
She, this sister, she lives in France, and she's been thinking of this too.
esuripo psuka yporape tkowsa te to Franse , ene skopneriijii'i somuire .
ɛsuɾipo psuka ipoɾape tkousa te to Fɾanse, ɛnɛ skopneɾihiʔi somwiɾe.
Ella, la nuestra hermana, viene de Francia, elle ha pensado tambien.
He was the first local authority, of the time I am telling in the past, and this relative of us was Pedro Ignacio Muiva.
emaripo ma mawgiene kparaakaeni , te to njitgiene te to konewokaeni / ene ema vjañonini Pedro Ignacio Muivuenri'i .
ɛmaɾipo ma mauçene kparakɨni, te to nhitçene te to konewokɨni ɛnɛ ɛma βhaɲonini Pedro Ignacio Mwiβwenɾiʔi.
El que fue la primer autoridad, lo estoy contando de antiguamente de nuestros parientes, que apeliraba PIM.
Now he was strong, in the past, he was defending this town.
juiti ema 'tumeri'i / kopeni ema / tkotyuchri'iniji pjoka 'wósare .
pas sûr que le n dans tkotgiuchri'iniji soit -ini. Pluriel serait devant ri'i (Cf. 2.035).
xwiti ɛma tumeɾiʔi kopeni ɛma tkotçuʧoɾiʔinihi phoka wosaɾe.
Ahora, el tenia fuerza antiguamente, habia defendio su pueblo.
and when they hated him, they were really hateful.
ene te to nakotichopuiji , eno tkotichonri'i .
ɛnɛ te to nakotiʧopwiçi ɛno tkotiʧonɾiʔi.
So now something because he... um... there is that um... statue near that platform.
tako'e juiti algo te to ema manje'eri'i , jenja pjuena maye'e estatua tachokio pjuena plataforma .
takoʔɛi (takoʔɛjɾiʔi) xwiti algo te to ɛma manheʔeɾiʔi, hɛnha pwhena majeʔe estatua taʧokjo pwhena platafoɾma.
Como él hize algo, está su estatua cerca de la plataforma.
And, and.. this... our relative the late Pedro Ignacio Muiva.
ene ene jmaro ... ma vjañonini Pedro Ignacio Muivueni .
ɛnɛ ɛnɛ hmaɾo ma βhaɲonini Pedro Ignacio Mwiβweni.
Allí este..., nuestro pariente, el difunto PIM.
and his stories, when... they had him killed, when um... they killed him.
ene to maye'e 'chojriikowono te to , eto ... ( timkopachoo'i ) [ timkopareko ...] te to manje'e nakopakopo .
"timkopareko" est une correction faite lors de la transcription
ɛnɛ tomajeʔe ʔʧoxɾikowono te to, ɛto timkopaɾeko (*timkopachoo'i erreur) to manheʔe nakopakopo.
Like Jesus Christ, they made things, they crucified him when they took him in order to beat him with the whip.
kutri'i ma jesukristo , najichri'i nakajapowikri'i te to nompuiji te to naestakri'i te to chkote .
kutɾiʔi ma xesukɾisto, nahiʧɾiʔi nakahapowikɾiʔi te to nompwihi te to næstakɾiʔi te to ʧkote.
Igualito como JC, lo hicieron cosas, lo crucificaron, cuando lo estaban llevando para la guasca.
They mistreated him, there was no one to defend him.
Esas cosas lo hicieron, no hay nadie para defenderle.
And there they took him, on the route to San Pedro.
ene eneji naemyon'o te pjuena tayonroku te to San Pedro .
ɛnɛ ɛnɛhi næmjonʔo:ʔi te pwhena tajonɾoku te to San Pedro.
Alli, lo levaron alli de ida a San Pedro.
There is where they msitreated the poor late Pedro Ignacio Muiva.
eneji te to naemponnojsi'ri'i ema powre viya Pedro Ignacio Muivueni .
eneji te to naemponosi'ri'i ema povre viya Pedro Ignacio Mwivweni.
Allí ellos maltrataron el pobre difunto Señor PIM.

And there was also the other authority of over there where I was born, a place called San Lorenzo de Mojos, there was also late Sir Santos Noco Guaji, he... they... um... they... were students in the old days.

ene emapo ma pona kparaakaeni te pjuena nutsine San Lorenzo de Mojo najichgieneri'i / emapo viya Santos Noko Wajinri'i , emarichu ema , eno ... manje'e ... eno ... 'esturiarekonri'i te to konewokaeni .
ɛnɛ ɛmapo ma pona kparakɨni te pwhena nutsine San lorenzo de Moxo hahitçeneɾiʔi ɛmapo βija Santos nokowaxinɾiʔi, ɛmaɾiʧu ɛma, ɛno manheʔe ɛno estuɾjaɾekonɾiʔi te to konewokɨni.
Tambien e otro que era autoridad alli donde naci, que nombraron San Lorenzo de Moxos, él, el difunto Señor Santos Noco Guaji, cuando (?) él estudio antiguamente.
So they could understand him (because he spoke Spanish) when um... he was defending our relatives.
tako'e ema eno techemra'onri'i eno te to manje'e makotyuchwokri'i eno vjañonono .
takoʔe ema ɛno te.ʧe.mɾa.hon.ɾi.ʔi ɛno te to manheʔe makotçuʧwokɾiʔi ɛno βhaɲonono.
El era el unico hombre que ellos entendian (porque hablaba castellano) y que defendia nuestros parientes.
In the past, in the days when the whip was still used,
our relatives were slaves, they were slaves, our poor relatives
eno no vjañonono eskravonri'ini , eskravonri'ini eno no vjañonchichano .
ɛno no βhaɲonono eskɾaβonɾiʔini, eskɾaβonɾiʔini ɛno βhaɲonʧiʧano.
nuestros parientes eran esclavos, eran esclavos nuestros pobres parientes.
They mistreated them, they employed him (exploited him), they were weeding (the fields), they were doing their tasks, they told.
naemponnojkoo'i , ( naempatron ... nkopatrononri'i ...) naempatronrikri'i , tiso'onri'i , nave'ri'i to tarea , nako'e .
næponoxko:ʔi, næmpaʧonɾikɾiʔi, tisoʔonɾiʔi, naβeʔɾiʔi to tarea, nakoʔe.
est-ce imi+patron (normalement jamais avec V), emprunt de empatronar, ou imi + V patrroriko ?
Ellos lo hicieron cosas, lo empatronaban, estan carpiendo, ellos estan sacando su tarea, dicen.
So when they weren't um... finishing their chores then they were whippinh them, they were mistreating our poor relatives.
tako'e to wo'ojno manje'ena ... naeta to naye'e tarea ene naestakri'i , naemponnojko no powre vjañonini .
takoʔe te to woʔoxno manheʔena næta to najeʔe taɾea ɛnɛ næstakɾiʔi, næponoxko no poβɾe βhaɲonini.
Cuando no sacan (su tarea), le dan guasca, hacen cosas a nuestros pobres parientes.
